04288nam a2200637Ia 9781501733796DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20191992nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017337967 a10.7591/97815017337962doi  a(DE-B1597)534398  a(OCoLC)1129161941  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJA79 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a172qOCoLC223/eng/202302161 aColes, Romand, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSelf/Power/Other :bPolitical Theory and Dialogical Ethics /cRomand Coles. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1992  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction: From Edge of Darkness to Ecotone -- t2. Augustine -- t3. Foucault -- t4. Merleau-Ponty -- t5. Conclusion: Possibilities and Dangers -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRomand Coles here explores the writings of Augustine, Foucault, and Merleau-Ponty in order to fashion an ethos that emphasizes the value of dialogical relationships between the self and others. In his view, each of these thinkers has made significant contributions that must figure in any reconsideration of the relationship between the self, ethics, and power.Whereas Augustine saw depth as the dimension of freedom and truth, according to Coles's reading, Foucault regarded depth as "that dimension in which we rout out the other and constitute ourselves in light of hegemonic norms implanted deep within us." After drawing out those aspects of Foucault's thought which point toward a "dialogical artistic ethics," Coles explores Merleau-Ponty's philosophy of depth, arguing that it elucidates the "intercorporeality" of the world in a way that emphasizes the value of our dialogical relations with different others. In conclusion, he brings the three thinkers together to assess their rhetorical and philosophical similarities and differences, and to argue against the tendency to see all post-modern thought as nihilistic and incapable of developing an ethico-political stance.Coles's highly original work seeks to provide an alternative to the positions that have structured most recent debate in political philosophy. Thus, his book points up difficulties in both the individualist and the communitarian readings of politics and ethics, even as it seriously explores the ethical dimensions and possibilities of post-modernist thought. His attempt to develop an ethos based on a specific conception of selves and the world enables him to cast provocative light on the continuing dialogue between rationalists and relativists about the nature of both selves and our social and political institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCommunities. 0aIndividualism. 0aPolitical ethics. 0aSocial ethics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173379640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501733796423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501733796/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles